# React + TypeScript (frontend)

## Types and exports

- Use `type` for props, DTOs, and unions. Use `interface` only for generated code (e.g. `routeTree.gen.ts`) or TanStack Router `Register` augmentation in `router.tsx`.
- Components and hooks: `export const Name = (...) => { ... }` (arrow functions). Avoid `export function` for UI unless a framework entry requires it.
- Prefer **named exports**. `export default` only where the framework demands it (e.g. NotFound route, devtools object).
- Use `import type { ... }` for compile-time-only symbols. When a module exports both types and values, use a separate `import type` line plus a value import (this repo’s ESLint disallows inline `import { type X }` with values in the same specifier list).

## Bad / good

```tsx
// BAD — interface for a component props bag
export interface CardProps { title: string }

// GOOD
export type CardProps = { title: string }
export const Card = (props: CardProps) => { ... }

// GOOD — type + value from same module
import type { Me } from '@/services/auth'
import { useMeQuery } from '@/services/auth'
```

Do not reformat third-party-style files under `components/ui/` unless changing behavior.
